}
```

```Explanations
Pressure Sensors (x8): These sensors convert pressure into an electrical signal. Strain gauge pressure sensors are used, outputting a maximum of 1 mV corresponding to the highest pressure.

Temperature Sensors (x8): Infrared detectors are used to measure surface temperature, providing an electrical signal proportional to the detected temperature up to a maximum of 100 mV.

Instrumentation Amplifiers (x8): These amplifiers are used to amplify the low voltage signals from the pressure and temperature sensors to a suitable level for the ADC. The amplifiers provide high input impedance, low output impedance, and precise gain setting to maintain the signal integrity and measurement accuracy.

16:1 Multiplexer: Since there are 16 sensors (8 pressure and 8 temperature) and the ADC samples one channel at a time, a multiplexer is used to sequentially select one of the 16 sensor signals to be sent to the ADC.

Sample & Hold: This circuit captures the selected sensor signal at a specific moment in time and holds it constant so that the ADC can accurately convert the analog signal to a digital value.

Anti-Aliasing Filter: This filter is placed before the ADC to remove high-frequency noise and signals above the Nyquist frequency, ensuring that the digitized signals accurately represent the original analog signals without aliasing artifacts.

Analog-to-Digital Converter (ADC): This component converts the analog signals from the sensors into digital data that can be processed by a microcontroller or processor.

Microcontroller/Processor: This block is responsible for coordinating the data acquisition process, including controlling the multiplexer, initiating the sample and hold, and reading the digital data from the ADC. It can process the data or communicate it to a computer for further analysis.
```

